        "markdown": "Codex’s diagnosis is basically right. After looking at the graph itself, I’d add four refinements.\n\nFirst, the declaration is not merely old-fashioned. It is internally vague. It names `task-graph-template-summary` as `primaryNodeViewId`, yet the declared `view` surface has no `viewNodeId` at all. The declaration also leaves `portViewNodeId` and `iconViewNodeId` empty. So the outward surface is partly implied through fallback behavior rather than explicitly wired. That is exactly the sort of hidden contract this hardening effort is meant to eliminate.\n\nSecond, I would avoid making the new port another synchronized state container. The clean chain should be:\n\n```text\ngoal / tasks / questions\n          ↓\n     updater script\n          ↓\n authoritative summary\n          ↓\n passive outward port\n```\n\nThe port should point at the summary through something like `sourceNodeId` and `sourcePayload`, or whatever the canonical modern equivalent is. The updater should not have to copy rollups into the port. Otherwise you replace the current dual-output model with a new dual-output model wearing a nicer hat. 🎩\n\nThird, I would define the **payload contract** before adding the port. The current summary contains useful derived fields such as goal, status, task progress, question progress, task titles, and question titles.  Decide which of those belong in the stable public payload and which are internal conveniences. A consumer should not silently become dependent on every field the summary happens to carry today.\n\nSomething along these lines:\n\n```text\ntaskGraphSummary.v1\n- title\n- status\n- completedTasks\n- totalTasks\n- answeredQuestions\n- totalQuestions\n- summary\n- target\n```\n\nThat gives the port an actual contract rather than merely a pretty rendering.\n\nFourth, I would isolate legacy compatibility aggressively. The `summary-task` node is a real `task` node, which means generic task scans must remember to exclude it. That is conceptually hazardous even if the updater already knows how.  If it must remain, I’d mark it unmistakably:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"countAsTask\": false,\n  \"compatibilityRole\": \"legacy-task-summary-consumer\",\n  \"deprecated\": true\n}\n```\n\nPossibly also hide it by default. A compatibility shim should look like scaffolding, not like a first-class room in the house.\n\nSo my preferred migration would be:\n\n1. Keep `summary` as authoritative derived state.\n2. Define a small versioned outward summary payload.\n3. Add a real passive port sourced from that summary.\n4. Point the declaration’s default surface explicitly at the port.\n5. Rename the fake `...-port` bridges.\n6. Quarantine `summary-task`, then remove it when the old consumer path is gone.\n\nThe extra principle I’d state plainly in the contract is:\n\n> **Views and ports expose state; they do not own or synthesize it.**\n\nThat sentence would prevent this same cloud from drifting into other templates later.\n",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "task-graph-template-declaration"
        },
        "_placement": {
          "version": 1,
          "state": "manually-shaped",
          "source": "manual",
          "updatedAt": 1784322365441,
          "reason": "node-drag"
        }
      }
    },
