      "data": {
        "memo": "",
        "link": "",
        "markdown": "Broadly, I think a task graph needs to exist at several scales. Not merely “small card” and “big graph,” but as an object that can be recognized, inspected, entered, operated, and composed with other graphs.\n\nThe cleanest model is probably a **surface ladder**:\n\n## 1. Identity surface\n\nThe smallest possible representation.\n\nThis is what appears in breadcrumbs, search results, compact references, graph selectors, navigation history, and tiny semantic-zoom states.\n\nIt should communicate:\n\n* title\n* icon\n* task-graph type\n* overall status\n* perhaps a tiny progress indicator\n\nThis is not the task itself. It is the graph’s passport photo.\n\n```text\n🛠 Task Graph Template\n3 of 7 complete\n```\n\nPossible declaration role:\n\n```text\nicon\n```\n\n## 2. Card surface\n\nThe primary outward `port`.\n\nThis is what another graph consumes when it wants to embed the task graph as an object. It should answer, at a glance:\n\n* What is being attempted?\n* What state is it in?\n* How far along is it?\n* Is anything blocked?\n* What is the next meaningful action?\n* Where do I enter it?\n\nThis should be the default surface because it represents the graph without exposing its machinery.\n\n```text\nGoal\nStatus\nProgress\nNext task\nOpen questions\nBlocked state\nEnter graph\n```\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\ncard\n```\n\nThis is the graph’s handshake with the rest of Twilite.\n\n## 3. Summary or document surface\n\nA readable, non-canvas representation of the entire plan.\n\nThis should synthesize the graph into something closer to a project brief:\n\n* goal\n* current status\n* task list\n* open questions\n* decisions\n* blockers\n* completed work\n* next steps\n\nThis is valuable for readers who want the meaning of the task graph without navigating spatially.\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\nsummary\n```\n\nor:\n\n```text\ndocument\n```\n\nI would keep this distinct from the card. The card is an invitation; the document is a report.\n\n## 4. Operational workspace surface\n\nThe full graph-authoring experience.\n\nThis is where the graph is entered and worked on:\n\n* create and edit tasks\n* connect dependencies\n* answer questions\n* record decisions\n* run updater scripts\n* reorganize the plan\n* inspect class and bridge plumbing when appropriate\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\nworkspace\n```\n\nor:\n\n```text\nauthoring\n```\n\nThis is likely the graph’s normal full-screen destination, but it should not be its default embedded representation.\n\n## 5. Execution view\n\nA task graph also needs a view intended for **doing**, not understanding.\n\nThe authoring canvas may contain goals, decisions, questions, scripts, bridges, declarations, and other architectural furniture. An execution view should strip that down to actionable work:\n\n* ready tasks\n* blocked tasks\n* in-progress tasks\n* next actions\n* assigned actor\n* completion controls\n\nThis might be a list, board, queue, or focused task runner.\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\nexecution\n```\n\nThe distinction matters:\n\n> The workspace explains and modifies the plan.\n> The execution surface advances it.\n\nThat could become extremely useful once agents operate inside Twilite.\n\n## 6. Dependency view\n\nA task graph’s edges carry meaning that a card or list cannot show.\n\nA dependency view should expose:\n\n* what must happen first\n* what is blocked by what\n* parallel work streams\n* critical junctions\n* tasks with no path forward\n* tasks that unlock many others\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\ndependencies\n```\n\nThis could still be graph-shaped, but filtered to operational nodes and dependency relationships. No declaration nodes, class bridges, updater scripts, or other backstage rigging.\n\nIt is the clean architectural X-ray.\n\n## 7. Timeline or sequence view\n\nDependencies and chronology are related, but not identical.\n\nA timeline surface could show:\n\n* planned ordering\n* milestones\n* deadlines\n* completed events\n* decision dates\n* changes in status\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\ntimeline\n```\n\nNot every task graph needs dates. This should therefore be optional, but the surface role should be available when the graph has temporal information.\n\n## 8. Activity and history surface\n\nA proper task object should be able to explain what happened to it.\n\nThis view would show:\n\n* tasks created or completed\n* decisions made\n* questions resolved\n* status changes\n* agent actions\n* script runs\n* important graph revisions\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\nactivity\n```\n\nThis becomes especially important in an agent environment. Without it, the graph can show current truth but not how that truth arrived.\n\n## 9. Machine-readable surface\n\nThe visual port is for humans and host graphs. Agents and tools also need a stable semantic payload.\n\nThis should expose a deliberately small, versioned contract:\n\n```text\ntaskGraph.v1\n- graphId\n- title\n- goal\n- status\n- progress\n- blockers\n- nextActions\n- openQuestionCount\n- updatedAt\n- target\n```\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\ndata\n```\n\nor:\n\n```text\napi\n```\n\nI would not make this a visible card unless there is a debugging need. It may simply be a declared surface or payload contract behind the main port.\n\nThis is how the task graph becomes a dependable computational citizen rather than just a rendered artifact.\n\n## 10. Compatibility surface\n\nOnly where needed.\n\nThe current `summary-task` path fits here. It should be explicitly named as legacy and excluded from ordinary discovery.\n\nPossible role:\n\n```text\ncompatibility\n```\n\nIt should never be mistaken for the primary representation.\n\n---\n\n## The complete surface family\n\nI would envision the declaration eventually saying something conceptually like:\n\n```text\nicon           → smallest recognizable identity\ncard           → default outward port\nsummary        → readable synthesized report\nworkspace      → full authoring graph\nexecution      → actionable task queue or board\ndependencies   → filtered relationship graph\ntimeline       → chronological projection\nactivity       → history and changes\ndata           → stable machine payload\ncompatibility  → temporary legacy consumer surface\n```\n\nThat sounds like a lot, but they do not all need to be implemented immediately, and they do not all require distinct stored nodes.\n\nSome may be:\n\n* actual nodes\n* views backed by one authoritative summary\n* filtered projections of the graph\n* runtime render modes\n* declaration entries pointing at the same node with different intents\n\nThe important thing is that they are **different promises**.\n\n## The irreducible core\n\nFor a task graph to have a complete basic existence in Twilite, I think it minimally needs four:\n\n1. **Icon**, so it can be recognized.\n2. **Card port**, so it can be composed into other graphs.\n3. **Summary**, so it can be read.\n4. **Workspace**, so it can be entered and changed.\n\nThen the first truly task-specific additions should be:\n\n5. **Execution**, so work can be performed.\n6. **Dependencies**, so structure can be understood.\n7. **Activity**, so changes can be trusted.\n\nThat gives the task graph a life cycle:\n\n> Recognize it.\n> Embed it.\n> Read it.\n> Enter it.\n> Work it.\n> Understand it.\n> Audit it.\n\nThat feels like a full and proper existence in the Twilite Zone. 🌒\n",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "task-graph-template-declaration"
        },
